{"response": {"response": {"new_topic_settings": {"topic_id": 2971959, "num_watchers": 1, "watchers_avatars": "", "watchers_usernames": "", "num_named_watchers": 0}, "initialization_time": 1671691157, "posts": [{"post_id": 26634933, "topic_id": 2971959, "poster_id": 599245, "post_canonical": "Let $2^n, 5^n$ have the same starting digit $d$ for some natural number $n$. Find $d$", "username": "MathsinMaths", "reported": false, "is_thanked": false, "is_nothanked": false, "attachment": false, "thanks_received": 0, "nothanks_received": 0, "thankers": null, "deleted": false, "post_number": 1, "post_time": 1670163875, "num_edits": 1, "post_format": "bbcode", "last_edit_time": 1670163936, "last_editor_username": "MathsinMaths", "last_edit_reason": "", "admin": false, "avatar": "//avatar.artofproblemsolving.com/avatar_599245.png", "num_posts": 172, "editable": false, "deletable": false, "show_from_start": true, "show_from_end": true}, {"post_id": 26634945, "topic_id": 2971959, "poster_id": 537231, "post_canonical": "$2^5=32, 5^5=3125, d=3$", "username": "Lankou", "reported": false, "is_thanked": false, "is_nothanked": false, "attachment": false, "thanks_received": 0, "nothanks_received": 0, "thankers": null, "deleted": false, "post_number": 2, "post_time": 1670164160, "num_edits": 0, "post_format": "bbcode", "last_edit_time": 0, "last_editor_username": "", "last_edit_reason": "", "admin": false, "avatar": "//avatar.artofproblemsolving.com/avatar_537231.jpg?t=1583947532", "num_posts": 460, "editable": false, "deletable": false, "show_from_start": true, "show_from_end": true}, {"post_id": 26637797, "topic_id": 2971959, "poster_id": 209000, "post_canonical": "Let's show that $d=3$ is indeed the only option. If $d\\cdot 10^k\\le 2^n <(d+1)10^k, d\\cdot 10^l\\le 5^n< (d+1)10^l$ then $d^2\\cdot 10^{k+l} \\le 10^n < (d+1)^2 10^{k+l}\\iff d^2\\le 10^{n-k-l}< (d+1)^2 \\implies d=3$.", "username": "alexheinis", "reported": false, "is_thanked": false, "is_nothanked": false, "attachment": false, "thanks_received": 0, "nothanks_received": 0, "thankers": null, "deleted": false, "post_number": 3, "post_time": 1670192378, "num_edits": 0, "post_format": "bbcode", "last_edit_time": 0, "last_editor_username": "", "last_edit_reason": "", "admin": false, "avatar": "//avatar.artofproblemsolving.com/avatar_209000.png", "num_posts": 8026, "editable": false, "deletable": false, "show_from_start": true, "show_from_end": true}], "tags": [{"tag_id": 177, "tag_text": "number theory", "is_public": true, "is_visible": true}], "data_to_set_direct_on_topic": {"last_post_time": 1670192378, "last_poster_name": "alexheinis", "num_posts": 3, "last_update_time": 1670192378, "locked": false, "num_views": 161}, "time_in_script": 7.235050201416016, "cmty_status": "slow", "user_session_data": {"user_id": 1, "username": "Anonymous", "logged_in": false}}}, "topic_id": 2971959}
{"response": {"response": {"new_topic_settings": {"topic_id": 495607, "num_watchers": 0, "watchers_avatars": "", "watchers_usernames": "", "num_named_watchers": 0}, "initialization_time": 1724894775, "posts": [{"post_id": 2782678, "topic_id": 495607, "poster_id": 154686, "post_canonical": "Find all solution in $\\mathbb{N}$\n$2^{2^{x}}+1=17y$", "username": "metalari", "reported": false, "is_thanked": false, "is_nothanked": false, "attachment": false, "thanks_received": 2, "nothanks_received": 0, "thankers": "Adventure10, Mango247", "deleted": false, "post_number": 1, "post_time": 1345887280, "num_edits": 0, "post_format": "bbcode", "last_edit_time": 0, "last_editor_username": "", "last_edit_reason": "", "admin": false, "avatar": "//avatar.artofproblemsolving.com/avatar_154686.png", "num_posts": 88, "editable": false, "deletable": false, "show_from_start": true, "show_from_end": true}, {"post_id": 2782679, "topic_id": 495607, "poster_id": 86443, "post_canonical": "only solution $(2,1)$", "username": "roza2010", "reported": false, "is_thanked": false, "is_nothanked": false, "attachment": false, "thanks_received": 2, "nothanks_received": 1, "thankers": "Adventure10, Mango247", "deleted": false, "post_number": 2, "post_time": 1345887561, "num_edits": 1, "post_format": "bbcode", "last_edit_time": 1345892945, "last_editor_username": "roza2010", "last_edit_reason": "", "admin": false, "avatar": "//avatar.artofproblemsolving.com/avatar_86443.jpg", "num_posts": 2877, "editable": false, "deletable": false, "show_from_start": true, "show_from_end": true}, {"post_id": 2782701, "topic_id": 495607, "poster_id": 135501, "post_canonical": "[quote=\"roza2010\"]only solution $(1,1)$[/quote]\nhow come ?", "username": "Pheonix", "reported": false, "is_thanked": false, "is_nothanked": false, "attachment": false, "thanks_received": 2, "nothanks_received": 0, "thankers": "Adventure10, Mango247", "deleted": false, "post_number": 3, "post_time": 1345891404, "num_edits": 0, "post_format": "bbcode", "last_edit_time": 0, "last_editor_username": "", "last_edit_reason": "", "admin": false, "avatar": "//avatar.artofproblemsolving.com/avatar_135501.jpg", "num_posts": 538, "editable": false, "deletable": false, "show_from_start": true, "show_from_end": true}, {"post_id": 2782707, "topic_id": 495607, "poster_id": 64716, "post_canonical": "The multiplicative order of $2$ modulo $17$ is $8$, since $2^4 = 16 \\equiv -1 \\pmod{17}$. Therefore, if $x\\geq 3$, then $8 \\mid 2^x$, and so $2^{2^x} \\equiv 1 \\pmod{17}$. So $x\\leq 2$, and so the only solution is $(x,y) = (2,1)$.", "username": "mavropnevma", "reported": false, "is_thanked": false, "is_nothanked": false, "attachment": false, "thanks_received": 2, "nothanks_received": 0, "thankers": "Adventure10, Mango247", "deleted": false, "post_number": 4, "post_time": 1345892209, "num_edits": 0, "post_format": "bbcode", "last_edit_time": 0, "last_editor_username": "", "last_edit_reason": "", "admin": false, "avatar": "//avatar.artofproblemsolving.com/avatar_64716.png", "num_posts": 15142, "editable": false, "deletable": false, "show_from_start": true, "show_from_end": true}], "tags": [{"tag_id": 178, "tag_text": "modular arithmetic", "is_public": true, "is_visible": true}], "data_to_set_direct_on_topic": {"last_post_time": 1345892209, "last_poster_name": "mavropnevma", "num_posts": 4, "last_update_time": 1724506174, "locked": false, "num_views": 75}, "time_in_script": 25.993824005126953, "cmty_status": "slow", "user_session_data": {"user_id": 1, "username": "Anonymous", "logged_in": false, "initialized": false, "logged_in_and_initialized": false}}}, "topic_id": 495607}
{"response": {"response": {"new_topic_settings": {"topic_id": 1766376, "num_watchers": 0, "watchers_avatars": "", "watchers_usernames": "", "num_named_watchers": 0}, "initialization_time": 1724908012, "posts": [{"post_id": 11567928, "topic_id": 1766376, "poster_id": 361561, "post_canonical": "Let ABC be a triangle with AB not equal to AC.Point E is there such AE=BE and BE is perpendicular to BC.Also point F such as AF=CF and CF perpendicular to BC.Let D be a point on BC such as AD is tangent to the circumcircle of ABC.Prove D, E, F are collinear.", "username": "Angelaangie", "reported": false, "is_thanked": false, "is_nothanked": false, "attachment": false, "thanks_received": 1, "nothanks_received": 0, "thankers": "Adventure10", "deleted": false, "post_number": 1, "post_time": 1547212371, "num_edits": 0, "post_format": "bbcode", "last_edit_time": 0, "last_editor_username": "", "last_edit_reason": "", "admin": false, "avatar": "//avatar.artofproblemsolving.com/avatar_361561.png", "num_posts": 151, "editable": false, "deletable": false, "show_from_start": true, "show_from_end": true}, {"post_id": 11568006, "topic_id": 1766376, "poster_id": 410090, "post_canonical": "Denote $E$ and $F$ by $O_b,O_c$ respectively. Note that $ABC\\sim COO_b$ where $O$ is the circumcenter of $ABC$. Thus, $CO_b=\\frac{R\\cdot b}{c}$. Similarly evaluating $BO_c$, we have $\\frac{BO_c}{CO_b}=\\frac{c^2}{b^2}=\\frac{DB}{DC}$. Note that $BO_c\\parallel CO_b$. Thus $D,O_b,O_c$ are collinear. $\\blacksquare$.", "username": "Synthetic_Potato", "reported": false, "is_thanked": false, "is_nothanked": false, "attachment": false, "thanks_received": 3, "nothanks_received": 0, "thankers": "Adventure10, Mango247, Mango247", "deleted": false, "post_number": 2, "post_time": 1547214228, "num_edits": 0, "post_format": "bbcode", "last_edit_time": 0, "last_editor_username": "", "last_edit_reason": "", "admin": false, "avatar": "//avatar.artofproblemsolving.com/avatar_410090.jpeg?t=1594470659", "num_posts": 114, "editable": false, "deletable": false, "show_from_start": true, "show_from_end": true}, {"post_id": 11570110, "topic_id": 1766376, "poster_id": 361561, "post_canonical": "Great, but how you got DB/DC=c^2/b^2", "username": "Angelaangie", "reported": false, "is_thanked": false, "is_nothanked": false, "attachment": false, "thanks_received": 4, "nothanks_received": 0, "thankers": "Adventure10, Mango247, Mango247, Mango247", "deleted": false, "post_number": 3, "post_time": 1547243479, "num_edits": 0, "post_format": "bbcode", "last_edit_time": 0, "last_editor_username": "", "last_edit_reason": "", "admin": false, "avatar": "//avatar.artofproblemsolving.com/avatar_361561.png", "num_posts": 151, "editable": false, "deletable": false, "show_from_start": true, "show_from_end": true}, {"post_id": 11572641, "topic_id": 1766376, "poster_id": 431628, "post_canonical": "[quote=Angelaangie]Great, but how you got DB/DC=c^2/b^2[/quote]\n\nas $DS$ is tangent to $(ABC)$ $\\triangle DAB \\sim \\triangle DCA$ so $\\frac{DA}{DC}=\\frac{c}{b}$ and from power of a point $DA^2=DB.DC$ and hence $\\frac {DB}{DC}=\\frac {DA^2}{DB^2}$\nNice solution synthetic potato I also have the same solution :) ..", "username": "omriya200", "reported": false, "is_thanked": false, "is_nothanked": false, "attachment": false, "thanks_received": 2, "nothanks_received": 0, "thankers": "RAMUGAUSS, Adventure10", "deleted": false, "post_number": 4, "post_time": 1547264612, "num_edits": 0, "post_format": "bbcode", "last_edit_time": 0, "last_editor_username": "", "last_edit_reason": "", "admin": false, "avatar": "//avatar.artofproblemsolving.com/avatar_431628.jpg?t=1577968531", "num_posts": 317, "editable": false, "deletable": false, "show_from_start": true, "show_from_end": true}, {"post_id": 11573104, "topic_id": 1766376, "poster_id": 361561, "post_canonical": "[quote=omriya200][quote=Angelaangie]Great, but how you got DB/DC=c^2/b^2[/quote]\n\nas $DS$ is tangent to $(ABC)$ $\\triangle DAB \\sim \\triangle DCA$ so $\\frac{DA}{DC}=\\frac{c}{b}$ and from power of a point $DA^2=DB.DC$ and hence $\\frac {DB}{DC}=\\frac {DA^2}{DB^2}$\nNice solution synthetic potato I also have the same solution :) ..[/quote]\n\nThanks\n", "username": "Angelaangie", "reported": false, "is_thanked": false, "is_nothanked": false, "attachment": false, "thanks_received": 2, "nothanks_received": 0, "thankers": "Adventure10, Mango247", "deleted": false, "post_number": 5, "post_time": 1547273821, "num_edits": 0, "post_format": "bbcode", "last_edit_time": 0, "last_editor_username": "", "last_edit_reason": "", "admin": false, "avatar": "//avatar.artofproblemsolving.com/avatar_361561.png", "num_posts": 151, "editable": false, "deletable": false, "show_from_start": true, "show_from_end": true}, {"post_id": 11880368, "topic_id": 1766376, "poster_id": 447719, "post_canonical": "Here is my solution for this problem \n[b]Solution[/b] \nLet $M$, $N$ be midpoints of $AB$, $AC$ \nWe have: $\\dfrac{DB}{DC}$ = $\\dfrac{AB^2}{AC^2}$ = $\\dfrac{BM}{CN}$ . $\\dfrac{sin \\widehat{ACB}}{sin \\widehat{ABC}}$ = $\\dfrac{BM}{sin \\widehat{ABC}}$ . $\\dfrac{sin \\widehat{ACB}}{CN}$ = $\\dfrac{BE}{CF}$ \nSo: $D$, $E$, $F$ are collinear", "username": "khanhnx", "reported": false, "is_thanked": false, "is_nothanked": false, "attachment": false, "thanks_received": 2, "nothanks_received": 0, "thankers": "Adventure10, Mango247", "deleted": false, "post_number": 6, "post_time": 1551539364, "num_edits": 1, "post_format": "bbcode", "last_edit_time": 1551539419, "last_editor_username": "khanhnx", "last_edit_reason": "", "admin": false, "avatar": "//avatar.artofproblemsolving.com/avatar_447719.png", "num_posts": 1595, "editable": false, "deletable": false, "show_from_start": true, "show_from_end": true}], "tags": [{"tag_id": 315, "tag_text": "geometry unsolved", "is_public": true, "is_visible": true}, {"tag_id": 48, "tag_text": "geometry", "is_public": true, "is_visible": true}], "data_to_set_direct_on_topic": {"last_post_time": 1551539364, "last_poster_name": "khanhnx", "num_posts": 6, "last_update_time": 1724512071, "locked": false, "num_views": 420}, "time_in_script": 27.20189094543457, "cmty_status": "slow", "user_session_data": {"user_id": 1, "username": "Anonymous", "logged_in": false, "initialized": false, "logged_in_and_initialized": false}}}, "topic_id": 1766376}
